Use case¶

Pneumonia is a serious lung disease that can lead to severe health complications if not diagnosed and treated promptly. One effective way to detect pneumonia is through the analysis of chest X-ray images. This dataset provides chest X-ray images of patients, including those diagnosed with pneumonia and those without the disease.

The objective is to develop a machine learning model capable of classifying these X-rays and accurately predicting whether a patient has pneumonia. By leveraging this model, healthcare professionals can streamline the diagnostic process, enabling faster and more reliable detection of the disease, ultimately improving patient outcomes and reducing the burden on radiologists.

import shutil
import os

# Define source and destination directories
source_dir = "Project_2/chest_xray/"
destination_dir = "data_dir"

# Create the destination directory if it doesn't exist
if not os.path.exists(destination_dir):
    os.makedirs(destination_dir)

# Copy 'train' and 'test' folders to the new directory
folders_to_copy = ['train', 'test']
for folder in folders_to_copy:
    source_folder = os.path.join(source_dir, folder)
    destination_folder = os.path.join(destination_dir, folder)
    if os.path.exists(source_folder):
        shutil.copytree(source_folder, destination_folder, dirs_exist_ok=True)
        print(f"Copied {folder} to {destination_dir}.")
    else:
        print(f"Folder {folder} does not exist in the source directory.")

# Remove the folder '2' from the destination directory
folder_to_remove = os.path.join(destination_dir, '2')
if os.path.exists(folder_to_remove):
    shutil.rmtree(folder_to_remove)
    print(f"Removed folder: {folder_to_remove}")
else:
    print(f"Folder '2' does not exist in {destination_dir}.")

# Function to list all subdirectories and count photos
def count_photos_in_folders(directory):
    folder_counts = {}
    for root, dirs, files in os.walk(directory):
        # Only count files with image extensions
        image_files = [f for f in files if f.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg'))]
        folder_name = os.path.relpath(root, directory)  # Relative folder name
        folder_counts[folder_name] = len(image_files)
    return folder_counts

# Check the directory structure and count photos
photo_counts = count_photos_in_folders(destination_dir)

# Print the structure and photo counts
if photo_counts:
    for folder, count in photo_counts.items():
        print(f"Folder '{folder}': {count} photos")
else:
    print("No photos found in the directory structure.")

In [10]:



     


import os
import random
import shutil

# Define paths
train_dir = os.path.join(destination_dir, 'train')
val_dir = os.path.join(destination_dir, 'val')

# Ensure the validation directory exists
if not os.path.exists(val_dir):
    os.makedirs(val_dir)

# Split the train data
for class_name in os.listdir(train_dir):
    class_train_dir = os.path.join(train_dir, class_name)
    class_val_dir = os.path.join(val_dir, class_name)

    # Skip if not a directory
    if not os.path.isdir(class_train_dir):
        continue

    # Create the corresponding class directory in validation
    if not os.path.exists(class_val_dir):
        os.makedirs(class_val_dir)

    # Get all images in the class directory
    images = [img for img in os.listdir(class_train_dir) if img.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg'))]

    # Shuffle and split into 80% train and 20% validation
    random.shuffle(images)
    split_index = int(len(images) * 0.9)
    train_images = images[:split_index]
    val_images = images[split_index:]

    # Move validation images to the validation directory
    for val_image in val_images:
        src_path = os.path.join(class_train_dir, val_image)
        dest_path = os.path.join(class_val_dir, val_image)
        shutil.move(src_path, dest_path)

    # Debugging: Print the process
    print(f"Class '{class_name}' - Moved {len(val_images)} images to validation directory.")

print("Validation directory created and data split completed.")



     




















    
    






Class 'PNEUMONIA' - Moved 388 images to validation directory.

Validation directory created and data split completed.

# Initialize counters for Pneumonia and Normal images
pneumonia_count = 0
normal_count = 0

# Iterate through the batches in the training dataset
for images, labels in train:
    pneumonia_count += tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(labels == 0, tf.int32)).numpy()  # Count images with label 0 (Pneumonia)
    normal_count += tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(labels == 1, tf.int32)).numpy()     # Count images with label 1 (Normal)

print(f"Pneumonia images in train: {pneumonia_count}")
print(f"Normal images in train: {normal_count}")

# Repeat the same for validation and test datasets
val_pneumonia_count = 0
val_normal_count = 0
for images, labels in val:
    val_pneumonia_count += tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(labels == 0, tf.int32)).numpy()  # Count images with label 0 (Pneumonia)
    val_normal_count += tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(labels == 1, tf.int32)).numpy()     # Count images with label 1 (Normal)

print(f"Pneumonia images in val: {val_pneumonia_count}")
print(f"Normal images in val: {val_normal_count}")

# For Test Set
test_pneumonia_count = 0
test_normal_count = 0
for images, labels in test:
    test_pneumonia_count += tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(labels == 0, tf.int32)).numpy()  # Count images with label 0 (Pneumonia)
    test_normal_count += tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(labels == 1, tf.int32)).numpy()     # Count images with label 1 (Normal)

print(f"Pneumonia images in test: {test_pneumonia_count}")
print(f"Normal images in test: {test_normal_count}")

Plotting the image for each label¶


















In [31]:



     


import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import tensorflow as tf

# Extract one image from each class (Normal and Pneumonia) in the train dataset
normal_image = None
pneumonia_image = None

# Iterate through the dataset
for image, label in train.take(1):
    # Check the label for Normal (0) and Pneumonia (1)
    # Iterate through each label in the batch
    for i in range(len(label)):
        if label.numpy()[i] == 0:  # Normal class
            normal_image = image[i].numpy()  # Get the corresponding image in the batch
            break  # Exit loop once a Normal image is found

    # Iterate through each label in the batch
    for i in range(len(label)):
        if label.numpy()[i] == 1:  # Pneumonia class
            pneumonia_image = image[i].numpy()  # Get the corresponding image in the batch
            break  # Exit loop once a Pneumonia image is found

    if normal_image is not None and pneumonia_image is not None:
        break

# Plot the Normal and Pneumonia images
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 5))

# Plot Normal image
axes[0].imshow(normal_image)
axes[0].set_title('Normal Image')
axes[0].axis('off')  # Hide axes for better visualization

# Plot Pneumonia image
axes[1].imshow(pneumonia_image)
axes[1].set_title('Pneumonia Image')
axes[1].axis('off')  # Hide axes for better visualization

plt.show()

import tensorflow as tf


# Load images and labels into lists for minority (Normal) and majority (Pneumonia) classes
normal_images = []  # Normal class
pneumonia_images = []  # Pneumonia class
normal_labels = []  # Normal labels
pneumonia_labels = []  # Pneumonia labels

# Unbatch the dataset
for images, labels in train.unbatch():
    if labels.numpy() == 0:  # Normal class
        normal_images.append(images.numpy())
        normal_labels.append(labels.numpy())
    elif labels.numpy() == 1:  # Pneumonia class
        pneumonia_images.append(images.numpy())
        pneumonia_labels.append(labels.numpy())

# Convert to NumPy arrays
normal_images = np.array(normal_images)
pneumonia_images = np.array(pneumonia_images)

# Print the shape of the NumPy arrays
print(f"Normal images: {normal_images.shape}")
print(f"Pneumonia images: {pneumonia_images.shape}")

Handling Class Bias using oversampling¶


















In [19]:



     


normal_dir = "data_dir/train/NORMAL"  # Path to NORMAL class folder
if not os.path.exists(normal_dir):
    os.makedirs(normal_dir)

# Augmentations for the NORMAL class (minority class)
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    #rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode="nearest"
)

# Load the dataset into separate lists for augmentation
normal_images = []
for images, labels in train.unbatch():
    if labels.numpy() == 1:  # Normal class
        normal_images.append(images.numpy())

normal_images = np.array(normal_images)

# Number of augmented images to generate (based on desired balance)
n_augmentations = 2281
# Example: Generate 3000 new images

# Generate and save augmented images
augmented_count = 0
for image in datagen.flow(normal_images, batch_size=1, save_to_dir=normal_dir, save_prefix="aug_", save_format="jpeg"):
    augmented_count += 1
    if augmented_count >= n_augmentations:
        break

print(f"{augmented_count} augmented images saved to {normal_dir}.")

Normalising to make training process faster¶


















In [22]:



     


def normalize(image, label):
  # Normalize pixel values to the range [0, 1]
  image = tf.cast(image, tf.float32) / 255.0
  return image, label

# Apply normalization to the dataset
train = train.map(normalize)
val = val.map(normalize)
test = test.map(normalize)

Loading the base Vgg16 model and adding output layer¶


















In [34]:



     


# Load VGG16 without the top layer
vgg16_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(150, 150, 3))

# Freeze the convolutional base
vgg16_base.trainable = False

# Build a new model with the pre-trained base
model = Sequential([
    vgg16_base,
    Flatten(),
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')  # For binary classification
])

# Load VGG19 without the top layer
vgg19_base = VGG19(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(150, 150, 3))

# Freeze the convolutional base
vgg19_base.trainable = False

# Build a new model with the pre-trained base
model_VGG19 = Sequential([
    vgg19_base,
    Flatten(),
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')  # For binary classification
])

# Print the model summary to verify
model_VGG19.summary()

# Sample for each class
normal_sample = None
pneumonia_sample = None

for image_batch, label_batch in test:
  for i in range(len(label_batch)):
    if label_batch[i].numpy() == 0 and normal_sample is None:  # Assuming 0 represents Normal
      normal_sample = image_batch[i].numpy()
      normal_label = label_batch[i].numpy()
    elif label_batch[i].numpy() == 1 and pneumonia_sample is None:  # Assuming 1 represents Pneumonia
      pneumonia_sample = image_batch[i].numpy()
      pneumonia_label = label_batch[i].numpy()
  if normal_sample is not None and pneumonia_sample is not None:
    break

# Make predictions
normal_pred = test_model.predict(np.expand_dims(normal_sample, axis=0))
pneumonia_pred = test_model.predict(np.expand_dims(pneumonia_sample, axis=0))

print(f"Normal sample prediction: {normal_pred}")
print(f"Normal sample actual label: {normal_label}")

print(f"Pneumonia sample prediction: {pneumonia_pred}")
print(f"Pneumonia sample actual label: {pneumonia_label}")


# Display the images (optional)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.imshow(normal_sample)
plt.title(f"Normal (Pred: {normal_pred[0][0]:.2f}, Actual: {normal_label})")

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.imshow(pneumonia_sample)
plt.title(f"Pneumonia (Pred: {pneumonia_pred[0][0]:.2f}, Actual: {pneumonia_label})")

plt.show()

CONCLUSION¶
So as we saw above the accuracy for vgg19 model was 93% and for vgg16 model was 91%. By this we can say vgg19 performs better then Vgg16 on this dataset. VGG19 performs better as it has a deeper neural network than VGG16. Although we can see for VGG16 we have lower loss on test set which mean it is more confident in giving the prediction
